---
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";

const architectureNotes = [
  [
    "Clients stay thin",
    "The app and CLI own user interaction only. They do not import backend, macOS recorder, or capture-engine code.",
  ],
  [
    "One protocol for every client",
    "Both clients use the same newline-delimited JSON protocol over ~/.wrec/wrec.sock. Protocol version checks prevent mismatched clients and daemons from silently misbehaving.",
  ],
  [
    "Daemon owns recording state",
    "The Rust daemon is the source of truth for target listing, permissions, one active job, queued jobs, pause/resume/stop, history, metrics, and persisted events.",
  ],
  [
    "Frames stay native",
    "The daemon launches a separate Swift capture-engine process for each active job. ScreenCaptureKit feeds AVAssetWriter directly; Rust never copies, transforms, or encodes video frames.",
  ],
  [
    "Separate packages share one runtime shape",
    "The app package carries wrec-app, daemon, and capture-engine. The standalone CLI package carries wrec, daemon, and capture-engine.",
  ],
  [
    "Agent rule",
    "Use the CLI with --json, trust daemon job state, refresh target ids per task, and follow error.next for recoverable failures.",
  ],
];
---

<DocsLayout title="wrec architecture" current="architecture">
  <p>
    Two thin clients — the native SwiftUI menu-bar app (<code>wrec-app</code>)
    and the <code>wrec</code> CLI — talk to a local Rust daemon over the same Unix-socket
    JSON protocol. The daemon owns all recording state and drives a native Swift capture
    engine that does the actual pixel work: ScreenCaptureKit hands frames straight
    to AVAssetWriter, which writes the hardware-encoded <code>.mov</code>. Rust
    never touches frames.
  </p>

  <h2>Process boundaries</h2>
  <ol class="flow-list">
    <li>
      <strong><code>wrec-app</code> or <code>wrec</code></strong> discovers or starts
      the daemon, then sends a JSON request over <code>~/.wrec/wrec.sock</code>.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong><code>daemon</code></strong> resolves the target and settings, owns
      the queue and job lifecycle, and persists events and metrics.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong><code>capture-engine</code></strong> receives one resolved recording
      job and owns ScreenCaptureKit, AVAssetWriter, system audio, microphone input,
      pause, resume, and finalization.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>The <code>.mov</code> file</strong> is written by AVAssetWriter while
      status and metrics travel back through the daemon to either client.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <table>
    <tbody>
      {
        architectureNotes.map(([rule, reason]) => (
          <tr>
            <td>{rule}</td>
            <td>{reason}</td>
          </tr>
        ))
      }
    </tbody>
  </table>
</DocsLayout>
